2. Github Webhook
A GitHub Webhook triggers a Jenkins job automatically every time a developer pushes code or opens a pull request. It removes the need for 
Jenkins to constantly pull the repository for changes.
Note-Jenkins runs on the 8080 port, so for EC2 instance the 8080 port should be open for Anywhere-ipv4 so that any changes made in github
will trigger the job in Jenkins.

1. Configure the Jenkins Job
A. Open the Jenkins dashboard.
B. Select your pipeline or freestyle project and click Configure.
C. Under the Build Triggers section, check the box for GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling.
D. Click Save.

2. Configure the GitHub Repository
A. Navigate to your repository on GitHub.
B. Click Settings (the gear icon on the top menu bar).
C. Click Webhooks in the left sidebar.
D. Click the Add webhook button

3. Complete the Webhook Fields
A. Payload URL: Enter https://<your-jenkins-server-url>/github-webhook/ (The trailing slash is mandatory).
B. Content type: Select application/json.
C. Secret: Leave blank unless you have configured a secret token in Jenkins global security.
D. Which events: Select Just the push event (default) or Let me select individual events if you need Pull Request triggers.
E. Active: Ensure this checkbox is checked.
F. Click Add webhook.

4. Verify the Connection
A. Look at the Webhooks list in GitHub after saving.
B. A green checkmark indicates a successful 200 OK handshake response from Jenkins.
C. A red warning sign indicates a network or URL error (commonly caused by Jenkins running on a local localhost network that GitHub cannot
reach).

Troubleshooting Local Environments
If Jenkins is running on a local machine, you must expose it to the internet so GitHub can reach the payload URL. Use a tunneling tool 
like ngrok to create a public forwarding URL:

ngrok http 8080

